Right-wing populists triumph in Austria, they have 29 percent of the total
According to preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections in Austria have brought about a significant weakening of the two parties forming the present grand coalition, as well as a marked strengthening of the populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), where the position of the current President Wilhelm Molterer is seriously threatened, suffered particularly heavy losses.
On the other hand, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Carinthia's Governor Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to the political scene at national level.
According to preliminary results, the Socialists (SPÖ) remain the leading political force in the country with 29.8 percent of the vote, but compared with the 2006 elections, they lost 5.5 percent of the vote.
The ÖVP, which with 25.6 percent lost almost nine percent of the vote, ended up even worse.
This is the worst result for the two major parties of the post-war period, and for the People's Party, which triggered the early elections, the result is literally catastrophic.
In early July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a considerable lead over the SPÖ.
But the voters were clearly punishing them for letting the government fall.
From the first reactions to the results, speculation about the possible resignation of the party leader and current Vice-Chancellor Wilhelm Molterer was voiced.
Observers believe that this could happen as early as Monday, at the extraordinary party leadership meeting.
Such a development would facilitate the path to the outcome of the election which remains the most likely, namely the renewal of the SPÖ and ÖVP grand coalition.
Nevertheless, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Free Party (FPÖ) reportedly won 18 percent and the BZÖ 11 percent of the vote - the socialists at the same time expressed fears of a repeat of 1999, when the People's Party agreed with the populists (at that time the FPÖ was still unified, the BZÖ split from it in 2005) on a joint government, which even prompted sanctions from the European Union.
Haider, who has already said that he is ready to collaborate with any party and that he plans to return to Vienna, on the national political scene, apparently based on this development.
The last party to gain access to parliament was the Greens, but they lost slightly and fell from third to fifth place among the Austrian political parties.
Clearly, no other party crossed the four per cent threshold and got into parliament.
