The atmosphere is characterized by hard work and enthusiasm.
The seabed hides a world of little known resources.
There may be oil, minerals and other mineral resources, but also previously unknown living organisms, which may hold the key to developing a cancer drug.
A deeper depth than the land
The coastal states have begun to aspire with vigour to new underwater territories.
They are indeed exercising their rights according to a UN convention, which was agreed in 1982 at Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is especially the area of what is called the continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometres from the coast of the country in question.
The latter may, according to the Convention, have an exclusive claim to all the resources of the continental shelf.
'For the sake of simplicity, the continental shelf is the part of the seabed and its subsoil which is a natural extension of the continent under the sea.
It extends beyond the limits of the coastal sea, often also beyond the two hundred nautical miles which represent the exclusive economic zone", explains Mikulka.
The request from the country concerned to the Commission for the establishment of the external borders of the continental shelf must be supported by a large scientific and technical documentation, based on many costly prospects and measurements.
It is the result of several years of preparatory work.
"One of our roles is to provide the committee with legal and scientific-technical assistance.
The Commission has so far dealt with five applications, from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far, only the last three countries have been successful", adds Mikulka.
The success of Australia, which was the first to significantly expand its underwater possessions, has recently been a global phenomenon.
New Zealand, too, has gained territory - the extent of the seabed, which the commission assigned to it last week, is 1.6 million square kilometres, which is six times the size of the country.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in prospecting.
The future benefits of exploiting the seabed will be, as they project, inestimable.
Gradually, other countries will also submit their applications.
They can do so within ten years of ratifying the Montego Bay Convention.
At the end of the continental shelf begins the area of the ocean floor, which has been declared by convention to be "the common heritage of mankind".
No State is now in an exclusive position.
The right to extract in this zone is granted by an international institution established by convention.
"But let's not make a mistake, the seabed is not a Klondike", says the director Mikulka, exaggerating, adding that "its zones are precisely clearly defined and their regime anchored in a contract".
