Organisers report a growing number of bookings
It should be a good winter for German travel agencies:
In terms of bookings for the coming months, according to one study, turnover has increased significantly compared with the previous year - for the winter season, even by more than 30 per cent.
Despite the weak economic outlook, the German travel appetite remains insatiable, according to the study.
As regards bookings for the winter season, travel agencies recorded a turnover of more than 31 per cent compared with the same period last year, as the German Federation of Travel Agencies (DRV) reported in Berlin on Monday.
According to the survey by the GfK Market Research Institute, increasing numbers of bookings are already dominating the autumn months.
The sales figure would have risen to around 11 per cent more compared with 2007, the DRV said.
The sources of these results are the figures of GfK, which analyses monthly booking data from 1200 travel agencies and makes estimates for the overall market.
Travel bookings made since the end of August 2008 would be recorded.
The low value of the dollar would make travel to the USA particularly popular, the DRV said.
This would mean an increase of about one third in bookings.
Besides that, Spain, Turkey and Greece, as well as our country, would be particularly desirable destinations for Germans.
The President of the DRV, Klaus Laepple, explained that organized trips are particularly in demand.
In view of rising energy and food prices, costs would be "easier to calculate for the customer than for an individual trip".
Consumers can save money with discounts on early bookings or All Inclusive offers, Laepple said.
