Long before Turkey was even thinking of joining the European Union, the European powers were eager to penetrate its hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 paces from Asia, lies one of the finest relics of his fallen imperial ambition.
Hydarpasha Station was designed in a neo-Renaissance style by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu.
At least that's what the guides tell us.
The monument is arranged on horseback at the bottom of the platforms, with observation towers at each corner, like some German provincial town halls.
The stones are dirty.
The whole building is in ruins.
But once inside the vaulted ticket office, we have no doubt about the greatness of the company, which represents a gateway to the west.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German association, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, which was late in the game of imperialism, wanted to realize its medieval ambitions of domination through this railway that reaches Damascus, Baghdad and the land better known as Saudi Arabia.
But German imperialist ambitions collapsed during World War I.
His railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab irregulars.
The relative isolation of the surrounding region, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is over.
The British and the Imperial forces advanced beyond Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
But there was also bad news for the station in Hyderpasha.
In 1917, a train loaded with ammunition exploded destroying its subtle roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has been slowly falling apart, mired in the tangles of history.
But today, the railway passage to Anatolia and all the eastern points, at least symbolically, serves to emphasize the widening of Turkey's diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the AKP, has created a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of the surrounding region, brought about by the frozen borders of the Cold War
Now is the time for a new policy on commitments.
