Suat Kiniklioglu could have been a centre-right politician from any other party in Europe.
He's got a suit, a tie, and he even has a blackberry.
"the aim of this foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey now into its immediate neighbourhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly", he said.
Turkey has been cut off from its back country.
Now she must be looking east and west at the same time.
Neither of them did.
She had to do both.
"but, at a certain point, I asked if Turkey should not choose".
"Turkey", he said, "does not want to have to choose between the two".
He then pointed out an aspect which almost everyone I spoke to recited to me by heart: The Turkish railway does not only go to the Middle East, but also to the Caucasus and around the Black Sea, so it is as much an advantage for Europe and the United States as it is for Turkey itself.
With Turkey's integration, the message seems to draw a Europe traveling metaphorically on the railways to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha Station, after another sleepless night, I thought of those two Germans, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who watched this building being built 100 years ago.
