The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
To advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has taken inspiration from nature, particularly bees.
A Japanese company has created a robot that, by imitating the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
It's called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, and it represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Brand Management, the BR23C represents the rise of the Nissan safety shield.
This robot will allow the brand's vehicles to prevent collisions.
During its flight, each bee created its own personal oval-shaped space that looks a lot like the Nissan safety shield.
But most importantly, the bee's compound eyes, which can see at an angle of over 300 degrees and in all directions, allow it to fly uninterrupted within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers have developed what is called a laser range finder.
The computer detects obstacles within a two-meter radius and a 180-degree radius, calculates the distance to the object, and immediately sends a signal to the microprocessor to avoid the obstacle.
"The moment it detects an obstacle, the little robot will imitate the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by forking its wheels 90 degrees or more to avoid a collision.
The biggest difference from any other system in existence is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
If this were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, Director of the Displacement Laboratory and lead engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be turned up or down or diagonally; it can move only in two dimensions and according to what its wheels allow it to do, not in infinite directions like bees.
For this purpose, Nissan used a rotation function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot could avoid obstacles.
Every second this device only has to process information and act on that data.
It does not need to store the information or intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, which is why it can run continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
It may be surprising, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes".
This represents the first development car for new instant collision prevention technologies, a technology that will be introduced in production cars in about a decade according to Nissan.
The robot runs on lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and longer lasting than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be to adapt this device to a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
