Morgan Stanley opens its capital to MUFG
Morgan Stanley announced the entry of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), Japan's largest bank, into the round, which will pay out $9 billion to take 21% of its capital, a news greeted by a sharp drop in its stock price.
A week after unveiling a tentative agreement, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley's common stock at a unit price of $25.25 - a total of $3 billion.
The price taken is 19% below the book value of the securities at 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional USD 6 billion in the acquisition of convertible securities providing a 10% return and a conversion price of USD 31.25.
Morgan Stanley has stated that the overall transaction would be carried out on the basis of an average unit price of $29 or 28% above its current price.
Morgan Stanley stock was down 6.79% to $23.07 at 5:00 PM GMT.
"This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley's transition to banking holding status", explained John Mack, the chief executive officer of the US group.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new charter last week, which should allow it to diversify its business but bring it under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to take a much more cautious stance than before.
The terms of the deal presented on Monday also show that the deal has been modified in recent days: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to the Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
"A week ago", explained Toshihide Mizuno, the executive director of MUFG, in Tokyo, "we thought that the holding would be entirely composed of ordinary shares.
