Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
Rebuild the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Hugo Chávez of Venezuela, Evo Morales of Bolivia and Rafael Correa of Ecuador.
This Sunday, like his colleagues and friends, he was the third to put to the vote a draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished, with 64% of voters voting "yes" in the referendum, according to official results with 80% of the vote.
According to these results, the "no" vote was 28%, 7% of the votes were zero and 0.7% were white votes.
For the draft Constitution to pass, it had to get half the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls at the exit of the polling stations and a count by a non-governmental organisation announced a large victory for the "yes" vote, with 63% to 70% voting.
Rafael Correa had claimed the victory of his draft Constitution in the night from Sunday to Monday.
"The Constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly", he said, congratulating Ecuadorians at the governorate headquarters in Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales, but also by his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which was conducted in a calm manner by the Organization of American States (OAS) observation mission, focused on a 444-point text consolidating the "new socialism" advocated by the president.
The draft Constitution enshrines the power of the state over the economy, reserving for it the "development planning" of a country that lives mainly from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and the foreign exchange sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the bill also grants the head of state increased powers, which will allow him to serve up to two consecutive four-year terms and will give him the possibility to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and run for a second term in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President has begun to introduce in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also provides for the prohibition of the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US anti-drug operations.
19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando has launched an assault on the kidnappers of the 11 tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The 11 European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions who were held captive for ten days in the desert were safely returned to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they were released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in good shape, the hostages arrived at around 3:30 p.m. aboard a special aircraft at the al-Maza military base, docked at Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, by helicopter to the Maadi Hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examination.
They are in "good health", and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers", said Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna on the tarmac.
Captured on September 19th during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been tossed from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The group included 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the Aegyptous agency, which organised the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, transported by two helicopters, launched the assault in the night just before dawn.
"A gunfight occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest fleeing", said the official, who asked not to be named.
He said that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces unit "Blitz" had been sent to Sudan, where they were supported by German and Italian commandos.
The Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned from Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our intelligence men, the special forces", he said, without elaborating.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army had claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle carrying the kidnappers during a patrol, killing six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army claimed that they were linked to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudanese United Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
