When is a platform for history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalise part of Fortis bank
The Benelux countries are helping the Belgo-Dutch bank, the first European banking institution to be in distress as a result of the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalising it. e three countries are providing EUR 11.2 billion in support of this financial and insurance institution which also has interests in Hungary.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments reached agreement at the highest level on this matter, also calling on the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition officer.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis, which has been intensifying for more than a year, is for Fortis Bank.
In accordance with the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy back almost half (49%) of the bank's capital in each of the countries.
The bank will undoubtedly sell part of its holdings, among which, first of all, the activities, mainly insurance, which it acquired last year from the Dutch entity ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis shares started a dizzying fall. In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis were already revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to let it go bankrupt.
On Friday alone, the company's stock fell 12 percent, reaching its lowest level in 14 years.
Since January, stocks have fallen by more than two-thirds.
Taking into account the current value of the shares, the total value of the capital of the group is around EUR 14 billion, which, according to the company's management, is not realistic.
The company's management blames uncertainty overseas, in connection with the adoption of the US $700 billion bailout plan, for the fall in Fortis stock.
On Monday, the paper has already seen a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed to the bank's board of directors as its new CEO.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but had not yet received a substantive proposal.
The Belgian government had previously announced that investors should not worry, they would not lose their money.
No panic was felt among the bank's clientele and no agencies were assaulted.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent agencies and has also acquired leasing companies.
A fox in the henhouse
In America, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about his drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
'There are data protection programmes which bind the use of prescribing information to the consent of the data subject in all cases.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like giving your henhouse to a fox", Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescriptions, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the insured capital in case of damage dependent on the health condition of the customer, and if they feel that the risk is too great, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they would send candidates for a medical examination, and they would sign an insurance contract with them only after they heard the results.
For the last ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he easily obtains from pharmacies, the data on the person's purchases of medicines in the last eighteen months. From this, the program itself determines, what disease the person suffers from and what is his state of health.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol-lowering drugs, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts them in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this programme are in circulation, some of which determine a risk coefficient at the same time, so there is little left for the insurer to do other than paperwork.
One of the disadvantages of this program is that one drug can be used for different purposes, for example, some mixtures can be used for migraines or hot flashes, but can also be effective for depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others do not.
Companies have developed in research and data analysis, and they must obtain the patient's consent before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
Now they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for past failures.
Recently, some companies are also processing lab results and linking them to data on drug use, in this way they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, and controlling their use is becoming increasingly difficult.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill to extend the scope of government control over companies specialising in data provision is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard recognises that this is not enough and has therefore developed his programme further, which would make the transmission of data subject's exclusive consent a condition.
It is another question whether the person concerned is really free to give his or her consent, since if he or she refuses, the insurers do not sign an insurance contract with him or her.
So, in the end, the chickens depend on the fox's kindness.
The overall menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
As the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this topic also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other issues, largely global.
Today will also be a summit between France and India, where cooperation on atomic energy will be the main topic of discussion.
The European Union recognises that India is a major emerging democratic power which should be given a wider say in international affairs, but member countries have not yet been able to agree on their support for New Delhi's candidacy for permanent membership of the UN Security Council.
They did not dwell too much on this issue yesterday at the ninth summit in Marseille.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as the current President of the Union, and Commission President José Manuel Barroso and the Head of Foreign Affairs, Javier Solana, welcomed the Indian Prime Minister, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years they would double trade, which means an increase of well over 100 billion euros.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007 the trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be a very ambitious target.
In this respect, they have legally harmonised the 26 bilateral conventions with India on civil aviation, thus enabling air trade to grow in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009 at the latest.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, the EU's largest trading partner, and New Delhi, the EU's ninth largest trading partner.
The summit focused on global issues.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan was strongly condemned, as were all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a UN conference on this subject was discussed.
The completion of the Doha trade cycle has also been called for, although both have a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains committed to the energy and climate agenda, including a reduction of at least 20% of toxic emissions by 2020.
India also agreed on this, as well as the fact that a global market should be reached at the climate conference next year, and greenhouse gas emissions should be reduced by 50 percent by 2050.
They also want to prevent food prices from rising, and have supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian head of state is today in the French capital, where he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth twenty billion euros for the construction of Indian nuclear reactors.
According to the news agency, the deal is for 15 years.
