A large number of Italian publishers attended the Frankfurt International Book Fair.
More than 300 Italian publishers attended the 60th edition of the Buchmesse, the most important international event in the exchange of rights.
The Frankfurt International Book Fair is expecting more than 7 thousand exhibitors from 101 different countries to take up the 171,790 square metres of the fair with over 403 thousand titles on display, with Turkey as the guest of honour.
The Italian Government will be represented at the opening ceremony of the Italian Butterfly by the Undersecretary of the Ministry of Cultural Heritage and Activities, Francesco Maria Giro, who will be present in an institutional capacity, with a 264 m2 exhibition space.
It will be followed by a press conference in the Struktur Room, in the 5.0 Butterfly of the Buchmesse: an opportunity to present the figures, trends and prospects on the position of publishing in Italy.
The data show that the importance of books by foreign authors is gradually declining in relation to total Italian production, and in particular in relation to adult and children's books.
Found the plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of the plane of Steve Fosset, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The debris was found on a plateau at an elevation of 3,000 meters in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, no human remains, though.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson said: "The plane has been located, we have sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is the plane Steve Fosset was on the day he disappeared", he said at a news conference.
The sheriff's office said no human remains were found on or around the plane.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead.
The US Transportation Safety Bureau (TSA) said that a few hours after the wreckage was spotted, an investigative team sent to the scene identified the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington, Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset's personal effects were found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
It's two documents in Fosset's name, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was stopped a month after he disappeared.
The billionaire had earned himself a place in history through a long series of records.
On his sixth attempt, in 2002, he became the first man to complete a round-the-world flight in an aerostatic balloon - a two-week solo flight.
Three years later, he had flown around the world non-stop.
Among all these records, there is the one of flying at 15,445 meters in the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
